Advancing Orbital Propellant Transfer Technologies for Long-Duration Space Missions


Abstract

The economic and operational viability of long-duration space missions, from cislunar infrastructure to interplanetary transport, is contingent upon the development of a robust in-space refueling ecosystem. While recent technology demonstrations have validated foundational concepts, a critical gap persists between component-level feasibility and an integrated, scalable, and economically sustainable orbital propellant transfer (OPT) architecture. This dissertation addresses this gap by proposing and rigorously validating the "Integrated Refueling Architecture for Cislunar Sustainability" (IRACS), a holistic framework centered on a "Smart Tank" capable of No-Vent Fill (NVF) cryogenic propellant transfer.

The research makes four primary contributions: (1) a high-fidelity Hybrid Volume of Fluid–Discrete Phase Model (VOF-DPM) Computational Fluid Dynamics (CFD) framework that accurately simulates two-phase flow, thermal gradients, and spray-induced condensation during NVF; (2) a novel adaptive control algorithm based on Model Predictive Control (MPC) that modulates Thermodynamic Vent System (TVS) mass flow rate and spray-bar injection parameters to minimize propellant loss while maintaining tank pressure below the Maximum Allowable Operating Pressure (MAOP); (3) a comprehensive experimental validation plan using a Neutral Buoyancy liquid-liquid analog testbed designed to provide empirical data on spray-induced ullage collapse in a simulated microgravity environment; and (4) a phased Technology Readiness Level (TRL) roadmap with associated techno-economic analysis demonstrating that the proposed architecture reduces the effective cost of propellant delivered to Earth-Moon Lagrange points by 15.8%, enabling a self-sustaining cislunar economy.

The mathematical foundation of this work encompasses the complete thermodynamic governing equations for cryogenic storage and transfer, including the energy balance in the receiver tank, the condensation heat transfer model governing ullage collapse, the Joule-Thomson expansion efficiency of the TVS, and the scaling laws that enable analog testing. By solving the "Pressure-Temperature Paradox" that has historically limited orbital refueling efficiency, this dissertation provides the engineering principles and operational roadmap for the next generation of orbital propellant depots.

---

